div.p:
The Heads therefore according to which this Discourse is to be modell'd,
                  Reas. 1. must be those Reasons, the Bishop gives for the Abrogating of the Test: The firstof which is;
That it doth not onely diminish, but utterly destroy the natural Rights of Peerage, and turns the Birth-Right of the English Nobility into a Precarious Title.

Secondly it ought to be repealed, because of its dishonourable Birth, and Original;
Reas. 2. 
it being the first Born of Oates his Plot, and brought forth on purpose to give Credit and Reputation to the Perjury.
